Here is an implementation of the n-th Fibonacci number in JavaScript using a dynamic programming approach:

```
function fib(n) {
  if (n < 2) return n;
  let f = [0, 1];
  for (let i = 2; i <= n; i++) {
    f[i] = f[i - 1] + f[i - 2];
  }
  return f[n];
}
```

This function uses a simple array to store the Fibonacci numbers up to n. It initializes the array with the first two Fibonacci numbers, and then iterates through the array to calculate each subsequent number using the previous two numbers. The function returns the nth Fibonacci number from the array.

Note that this implementation is O(n) in time complexity and requires O(n) space. If memory is a concern, you can also use a more space-efficient approach such as memoization or iterative calculation.

